# /import-notes: Import Granola Meeting Notes

Every meeting recorded in Granola gets exported to Notion automatically. This skill reads those notes, figures out what type of meeting it was, and writes the structured entries — site reports, decisions, RFIs — to the right places.

---

## Step 1: Find unprocessed notes

Use the Notion MCP to query for pages that:
- Were created by Granola (check the "Created by" field or a "Source: Granola" property if configured)
- Do NOT have an "Imported" tag or property set to true

```
Query: Notion pages in workspace where source = "Granola" AND imported != true
Sort: by creation date, oldest first
Limit: 20 per run (don't try to process hundreds at once)
```

If no unprocessed notes are found: tell the owner and exit.

---

## Step 2: Classify each note

For each unprocessed Granola note, read the title and body and classify it:

| Classification | Signals |
|---|---|
| **Site visit** | "site visit," "walked the site," "on site," "GC walkthrough," "inspection" |
| **Architect meeting** | "arch meeting," "design review," "drawing review," "Zoom with architect" |
| **Contractor call** | "call with [name]," "phone with," "bid call," "scope call" |
| **Client/owner meeting** | "client meeting," "owner meeting," "stakeholder" (if you manage for others) |
| **Bid meeting** | "bid walk," "pre-bid meeting," "site walk for bid" |
| **Permit/jurisdiction meeting** | "pre-app meeting," "planning department," "building department" |
| **Internal planning** | "planning session," "project review," "budget review" |
| **Unknown** | Unclear from title and first paragraph |

---

## Step 3: Extract structured data by type

**Site visit → draft `/site-report` entry:**
- Date of visit
- Who was present
- Key observations (bullet points from the notes)
- Work completed since last visit
- Any open items or concerns raised
- Any informal scope change requests mentioned

**Architect meeting → update `design/options.md`:**
- Date
- Design decisions made or discussed
- Any open questions raised
- Action items with owner

**Contractor call → check for scope changes and decisions:**
- Was any pricing discussed? → potential `/cost-check` trigger
- Was any scope change requested or agreed to? → `/decide` entry needed
- Was a bid discussed? → log in `budget/bids/`

**Bid meeting → update `budget/bids/`:**
- Contractor name
- Scope discussed
- Any verbal pricing given

**Any note → scan for decisions:**
Regardless of meeting type, scan for:
- Any language indicating a decision was made: "we decided," "agreed to," "going with," "confirmed"
- Any cost figures mentioned
- Any schedule commitments made

---

## Step 4: Write structured entries

For each classified note, write the appropriate entries. Show the owner a preview before writing. Format:

```
[Meeting type] — [Date]
From: "[Note title]" in Notion

WILL WRITE:
→ Site report: construction/site-reports/site-report-[date].md
→ Decision entry: "we agreed to use the [X] windows" — cost impact: unknown (needs pricing)
→ RFI flagged: "[question from contractor about [thing]]"

SKIPPING:
→ Action item "confirm delivery date with supplier" — informational only

Proceed? [yes/skip/review]
```

Wait for owner confirmation before writing. If "review," show the full note and ask what to do.

---

## Step 5: Mark as imported

After writing all entries for a note, update the Notion page:
- Add the "Imported" tag or set `imported: true`
- Add a note with the date imported and what was created

---

## Step 6: Summary

After processing all notes:

```
Imported [N] meeting notes:
  ✓ [N] site reports written
  ✓ [N] decisions logged
  ✓ [N] RFIs flagged
  ✓ [N] budget items to price
  → [N] items need your review (shown above)
```

If there were any "unknown" classified notes: show them to the owner and ask how to categorize them.
